Caching is a techniques of storing frequently accessed data in a temporary storage location to improve the system performance. Caching helps to reduce the time and resources required to fetch the data from the original source by serving it quickly from the cache. Caching is a technique that allows frequently accessed data to be stored in memory so that it can be quickly retrieved without having to go back to the database every time. Web browser caches web pages to load them faster on subsequent visits. Database server caches frequently accessed query results to avoid expensive database queries.<div><br></div><div>Cacheable data: data that does not changes at all are the best candidate for caching and data that does not frequently changes can also be cached for certain period to time. Cache reduces latency and load on the database.</div><div><br></div><div>Cache eviction policy is an algorithm used to decide which data to remove from a cache when it is full, in order to make space for new data. The goal is to keep the most relevant and frequently accessed data in the cache to maintain performance.</div><div><br></div><div><table style="
            width: 100%;
