            font-weight: bold;
          ">TTL</td></tr><tr><td style="border: 1px solid rgb(204, 204, 204); padding: 8px; text-align: center;">Removes the data that has not been accessed for the longest time. When a new item is added and the cache is full, the oldest item is evicted. </td><td style="border: 1px solid rgb(204, 204, 204); padding: 8px; text-align: center;">Removes the data that has been accessed the fewest number of times. This policy assumes that infrequently used items are less valuable and less likely to be needed soon. </td><td style="border: 1px solid rgb(204, 204, 204); padding: 8px; text-align: center;">Removes the oldest data that was added to the cache, regardless of how frequently it was accessed. </td><td style="border: 1px solid rgb(204, 204, 204); padding: 8px; text-align: center;">Chooses a random item to evict when the cache is full. This is very fast but unpredictable and not suitable for most applications. </td><td style="border: 1px solid rgb(204, 204, 204); padding: 8px; text-align: center;">Evicts items after a specific amount of time has passed since they were added or last accessed, making it useful for time-sensitive data. </td></tr></tbody></table></div><div><br></div><div>Why cache eviction is important:</div><div>Manages limited cache size:</div><div>Caches have a finite amount of memory, and eviction ensures old or unused data is removed to make space for new data.</div><div>Improves performance:</div><div>By keeping the most relevant data in the cache, eviction policies can increase the cache hit rate and reduce access times.</div><div>Ensures data consistency:</div><div>Eviction can help ensure that data in the cache is not stale, especially for data that changes frequently. </div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div>
